<subSubSection id="85AC57D9C53BAA70FF3EFA1C532620E4" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="CD090452C53BAA70FF3EFA1C559E2029" blockId="3.[151,1437,1465,2033]" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">
<emphasis id="FFC2D840C53BAA70FF3EFA1C574022E3" bold="true" box="[199,315,1501,1526]" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">Remarks.</emphasis>
Adults of 
<taxonomicName id="0AB67FD1C53BAA70FE4AFA1F546622E3" box="[435,541,1501,1526]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="browni">
<emphasis id="FFC2D840C53BAA70FE4AFA1F546622E3" box="[435,541,1501,1526]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">P. browni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
display golden-brown background color with darker pigmentation on the head, thorax (
<figureCitation id="558D18D7C53BAA70FF0CF9C057F8210F" box="[245,387,1537,1562]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1305,1327]" captionTargetBox="[211,1383,297,1177]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,265,1218]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Perlesta browni. a–b, Arkansas, Fourche La Fave River; c–d, Arkansas, Ouachita River; a, c, male, head + pronotum, dorsal profile; b, d, female, head + pronotum, dorsal profile." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1301372/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">Figs. 3a‒3d</figureCitation>
), and abdomen. Whereas the abdominal terga for females are nearly uniform in color throughout their length, by comparison male terga 6‒10 are markedly darker than the anterior five segments. The posterolateral corners of the male 9th sternum are clothed by a dense matting of long hairs, noticeably longer and denser than the anterolateral and medial portions of the segment (
<figureCitation id="558D18D7C53BAA70FC5DF9B15587219C" box="[932,1020,1648,1673]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1659,1681]" captionTargetBox="[180,1392,226,1590]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,193,1637]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Perlesta browni, Arkansas, Fourche La Fave River. a, male, paraprocts, lateral view, 300X; b, male, paraprocts, caudal (left) and mostly lateral (right) views, 330X; c, male, right paraproct, lateral view 270X; d, male, 9 th sternum, 130X; e, egg, 330X; f, egg collar, anterior pole, 1100X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1301374/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">Fig. 4d</figureCitation>
). Males have long, slender, tubular paraprocts with a mesoapical tooth (
<figureCitation id="558D18D7C53BAA70FDC9F95554CF21B9" box="[560,692,1684,1709]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1659,1681]" captionTargetBox="[180,1392,226,1590]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,193,1637]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Perlesta browni, Arkansas, Fourche La Fave River. a, male, paraprocts, lateral view, 300X; b, male, paraprocts, caudal (left) and mostly lateral (right) views, 330X; c, male, right paraproct, lateral view 270X; d, male, 9 th sternum, 130X; e, egg, 330X; f, egg collar, anterior pole, 1100X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1301374/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">Figs. 4a‒4c</figureCitation>
) that are similar to sympatric 
<taxonomicName id="0AB67FD1C53BAA70FBF1F95452F321B9" authorityName=", Stark" authorityYear="2004" box="[1032,1160,1685,1708]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cinctipes">
<emphasis id="FFC2D840C53BAA70FBF1F95452F321B9" box="[1032,1160,1685,1708]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">P. cinctipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="558D18D7C53BAA70FB61F955536221B8" box="[1176,1305,1684,1709]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1839,1861]" captionTargetBox="[175,1408,392,1789]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,375,1820]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Perlesta cinctipes. a–b, Arkansas, unknown locality; c–f, Missouri, South Moreau Creek; a, c, male, head + pronotum, dorsal profile; b, d, female, head + pronotum, dorsal profile; e, right paraproct, lateral view, 180X; f, right paraproct, lateral view, 330X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1301376/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">Figs. 5e‒5f</figureCitation>
) but longer than those of 
<taxonomicName id="0AB67FD1C53BAA70FECFF97857BA21C5" authority="Grubbs &amp; Dewalt, 2018" authorityName="Grubbs &amp; Dewalt" authorityYear="2018" box="[310,449,1721,1744]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armitagei" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="FFC2D840C53BAA70FECFF97857BA21C5" box="[310,449,1721,1744]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">P. armitagei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="E4F1653BC53BAA70FE35F979545321C4" box="[460,552,1720,1745]" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" rank="species">
<emphasis id="FFC2D840C53BAA70FE35F979545321C4" bold="true" box="[460,552,1720,1745]" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
(
<figureCitation id="558D18D7C53BAA70FDC3F97954BF21C5" box="[570,708,1720,1745]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1683,1705]" captionTargetBox="[179,1408,214,1602]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,193,1659]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Perlesta armitagei sp. nov., male.; a, Ohio, Deer Creek, male, 9 th sternum, 130X; b, Indiana, Blue River, right paraproct, lateral, 370X; c, Pennsylvania, French Creek, paraprocts, dorsal, 450X; d, Pennsylvania, French Creek, paraprocts, caudal, 330X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1301380/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">Figs. 7a, 7c</figureCitation>
). In addition, 
<bibRefCitation id="A92779A3C53BAA70FC90F97952E921C5" box="[873,1170,1720,1745]" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" refId="ref8347" refString="Poulton, B. P. &amp; Stewart, K. W. (1991) Stoneflies of the Ozark and Ouachita Mountains (Plecoptera). Memoirs of the American Entomological Society, 13, 1 - 116. https: // biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 38911829" type="journal article">Poulton &amp; Stewart (1991)</bibRefCitation>
showed that 
<taxonomicName id="0AB67FD1C53BAA70FAD6F97853E021C4" box="[1327,1435,1720,1745]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="browni">
<emphasis id="FFC2D840C53BAA70FAD6F97853E021C4" box="[1327,1435,1720,1745]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">P. browni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
femora are pigmented only in the distal third, the brown color extending to the articulation with the tibia (their Fig. 344). Conversely, 
<taxonomicName id="0AB67FD1C53BAA70FE9EF8C05792200D" authorityName=", Stark" authorityYear="2004" box="[359,489,1793,1816]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cinctipes">
<emphasis id="FFC2D840C53BAA70FE9EF8C05792200D" box="[359,489,1793,1816]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">P. cinctipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
femora are pigmented in approximately the middle 40%, the articulations with the coxae and tibiae are unpigmented (
<bibRefCitation id="A92779A3C53BAA70FDE7F8E555A22029" box="[542,985,1828,1853]" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" refId="ref8347" refString="Poulton, B. P. &amp; Stewart, K. W. (1991) Stoneflies of the Ozark and Ouachita Mountains (Plecoptera). Memoirs of the American Entomological Society, 13, 1 - 116. https: // biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 38911829" type="journal article">Poulton &amp; Stewart 1991, their Fig. 342</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD090452C53BAA70FF3EF889532620E4" blockId="3.[151,1437,1465,2033]" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">
Females can be separated by characteristics of their subgenital plate lobes and median notch (
<bibRefCitation id="A92779A3C53BAA70FB27F88953252075" box="[1246,1374,1864,1889]" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" refId="ref8501" refString="Stark, B. P. (2004) Perlidae (The Stones). In: Stark, B. P. &amp; Armitage, B. J. (Eds.), The stoneflies (Plecoptera) of eastern North America. Vol. II. Chloroperlidae, Perlidae, and Perlodidae (Perlodinae). Bulletin of the Ohio Biological Survey. New Series. Uol. 14. Ohio Biological Society, Columbus, Ohio, pp. 61 - 148." type="journal article">Stark 2004</bibRefCitation>
). The eggs of 
<taxonomicName id="0AB67FD1C53BAA70FF0CF8AC571A2090" box="[245,353,1900,1925]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="browni">
<emphasis id="FFC2D840C53BAA70FF0CF8AC571A2090" box="[245,353,1900,1925]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">P. browni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are easily differentiated from 
<taxonomicName id="0AB67FD1C53BAA70FD3AF8AC553E2091" authorityName=", Stark" authorityYear="2004" box="[707,837,1901,1924]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cinctipes">
<emphasis id="FFC2D840C53BAA70FD3AF8AC553E2091" box="[707,837,1901,1924]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">P. cinctipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The egg of 
<taxonomicName id="0AB67FD1C53BAA70FC27F8AC52312090" box="[990,1098,1900,1925]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="browni">
<emphasis id="FFC2D840C53BAA70FC27F8AC52312090" box="[990,1098,1900,1925]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">P. browni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a short, slightly distallyflanged ribbed collar and the chorionic surface is covered by fine punctations except near the eclosion line (
<figureCitation id="558D18D7C53BAA70FA9DF85156A120D8" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1659,1681]" captionTargetBox="[180,1392,226,1590]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,193,1637]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Perlesta browni, Arkansas, Fourche La Fave River. a, male, paraprocts, lateral view, 300X; b, male, paraprocts, caudal (left) and mostly lateral (right) views, 330X; c, male, right paraproct, lateral view 270X; d, male, 9 th sternum, 130X; e, egg, 330X; f, egg collar, anterior pole, 1100X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1301374/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">Figs. 4e‒4f</figureCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="A92779A3C53BAA70FF1EF875571D20D9" box="[231,358,1972,1997]" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" refId="ref8452" refString="Stark, B. P. (1989) Perlesta placida (Hagen), an eastern Nearctic species complex (Plecoptera: Perlidae). Insect Systematics and Evolution, 20, 263 - 286. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631289 X 00339" type="journal article">Stark 1989</bibRefCitation>
, his Fig. 15). The egg of 
<taxonomicName id="0AB67FD1C53BAA70FD76F874556A20D9" authorityName=", Stark" authorityYear="2004" box="[655,785,1973,1996]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cinctipes">
<emphasis id="FFC2D840C53BAA70FD76F874556A20D9" box="[655,785,1973,1996]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">P. cinctipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a similar collar but the chorionic surface is coarsely pitted except for the smooth eclosion line region (
<bibRefCitation id="A92779A3C53BAA70FD3AF819553920E5" box="[707,834,2008,2033]" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" refId="ref8452" refString="Stark, B. P. (1989) Perlesta placida (Hagen), an eastern Nearctic species complex (Plecoptera: Perlidae). Insect Systematics and Evolution, 20, 263 - 286. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631289 X 00339" type="journal article">Stark 1989</bibRefCitation>
, his Fig. 17; 
<bibRefCitation id="A92779A3C53BAA70FC2AF819523420E5" box="[979,1103,2008,2033]" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" refId="ref8501" refString="Stark, B. P. (2004) Perlidae (The Stones). In: Stark, B. P. &amp; Armitage, B. J. (Eds.), The stoneflies (Plecoptera) of eastern North America. Vol. II. Chloroperlidae, Perlidae, and Perlodidae (Perlodinae). Bulletin of the Ohio Biological Survey. New Series. Uol. 14. Ohio Biological Society, Columbus, Ohio, pp. 61 - 148." type="journal article">Stark 2004</bibRefCitation>
, his Figs. 7.394‒7.396).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="85AC57D9C53CAA77FF3EFF5655C02609" pageId="4" pageNumber="87" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="CD090452C53CAA77FF3EFF5655C02609" blockId="4.[151,1436,151,285]" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">
<taxonomicName id="0AB67FD1C53CAA77FF3EFF56570027A5" box="[199,379,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="browni">
<emphasis id="FFC2D840C53CAA77FF3EFF56570027A5" box="[199,379,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">Perlesta browni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was considered endemic to the Interior Highland region (
<figureCitation id="558D18D7C53CAA77FBEBFF56520827A5" box="[1042,1139,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1938,1960]" captionTargetBox="[205,1400,405,1888]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[167,1431,373,1925]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 11. Distribution maps of Perlesta based on material examined during this study. a, P. adena, P. browni, P. cinctipes, and P. xube; b, P. armitagei sp. nov. The record from northern West Virginia (red circle; Tarter &amp; Nelson 2006) is conditional since that material was not available for study. The type locality is represented by the purple circle." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1301388/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">Fig. 11a</figureCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="A92779A3C53CAA77FB78FF5653EC27A5" box="[1153,1431,151,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="87" refId="ref8347" refString="Poulton, B. P. &amp; Stewart, K. W. (1991) Stoneflies of the Ozark and Ouachita Mountains (Plecoptera). Memoirs of the American Entomological Society, 13, 1 - 116. https: // biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 38911829" type="journal article">Poulton &amp; Stewart 1991</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="A92779A3C53CAA77FF6EFF7D576F27C1" box="[151,276,188,213]" pageId="4" pageNumber="87" refId="ref8501" refString="Stark, B. P. (2004) Perlidae (The Stones). In: Stark, B. P. &amp; Armitage, B. J. (Eds.), The stoneflies (Plecoptera) of eastern North America. Vol. II. Chloroperlidae, Perlidae, and Perlodidae (Perlodinae). Bulletin of the Ohio Biological Survey. New Series. Uol. 14. Ohio Biological Society, Columbus, Ohio, pp. 61 - 148." type="journal article">Stark 2004</bibRefCitation>
) until specimens seemingly indistinguishable from this species were reported from a single locality in eastern 
<collectingRegion id="0F72CAB0C53CAA77FF16FF1E573127ED" box="[239,330,223,248]" country="United States of America" name="Virginia" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">Virginia</collectingRegion>
(Kondratieff 
<emphasis id="FFC2D840C53CAA77FE10FF20545F27ED" box="[489,548,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">et al.</emphasis>
2011). 
<taxonomicName id="0AB67FD1C53CAA77FD84FF1E554A27ED" box="[637,817,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="browni">
<emphasis id="FFC2D840C53CAA77FD84FF1E554A27ED" box="[637,817,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">Perlesta browni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sympatric with 
<taxonomicName id="0AB67FD1C53CAA77FBF3FF2052F027ED" authorityName=", Stark" authorityYear="2004" box="[1034,1163,225,248]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cinctipes">
<emphasis id="FFC2D840C53CAA77FBF3FF2052F027ED" box="[1034,1163,225,248]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">P. cinctipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
mainly in the Ouachita Mountain region of western 
<collectingRegion id="0F72CAB0C53CAA77FE2CFEC554462608" box="[469,573,260,285]" country="United States of America" name="Arkansas" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">Arkansas</collectingRegion>
and eastern 
<collectingRegion id="0F72CAB0C53CAA77FD32FEC5553B2608" box="[715,832,260,285]" country="United States of America" name="Oklahoma" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">Oklahoma</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation id="558D18D7C53CAA77FCB6FEC555D62609" box="[847,941,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1938,1960]" captionTargetBox="[205,1400,405,1888]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[167,1431,373,1925]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 11. Distribution maps of Perlesta based on material examined during this study. a, P. adena, P. browni, P. cinctipes, and P. xube; b, P. armitagei sp. nov. The record from northern West Virginia (red circle; Tarter &amp; Nelson 2006) is conditional since that material was not available for study. The type locality is represented by the purple circle." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1301388/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">Fig. 11a</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
